	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">lord wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What is a "metatile"???</div>
<br />What the hell? Only Bregalad can answer now?
<br />
<br />Well, a metatile is a block, larger than 8x8 pixels, formed by more than 1 tile (wich is 8x8 pixels). Metatiles exist to make the level maps smaller. If you were to define a screen for a game directly using tiles, it would take 1kb (1024 bytes) to define the whole screen (tiles + attributes). But if you use 16x16 pixels (2x2 tiles) metatiles, there will be only 240 of them in a screen, wich means a screen can now be defined by only 240 bytes. That's a huge gain, 1024 to 240, don't you think?
<br />
<br />You have to define the metatiles in a separate space, of course. If you're using 16x16 pixels (2x2 tiles) metatiles, you'll have to define what 4 tiles that metatile uses. A common format for 16x16 metatiles uses 5 bytes for each, with 4 bytes indicating the tiles used to draw it, and the 5th byte indicating the palette to use for the block, and the type of the block (solid, sky, water, etc - stuff used for collision and physics)
<br />
<br />So, when you decode the map to the screen, you don't copy directly. You read a byte from the map, check what tiles make up that block and draw those tiles to the screen. And don't forget to properly set the attributes too.
<br />
<br />The most common size for metatiles is 16x16 pixels, but there are others like 32x16, 32x32, etc. Each one has it's pro's and con's. I guess that's it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


